University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Rutherford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rutherford","meanings":["Scottish and northern English: habitational name from Rutherford in Maxton (Roxburghshire), apparently named with Old English <i>hrīther</i>, <i>hrȳther</i> ‘ox’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, though a British Celtic origin of the type <i>ro-</i> ‘great’ + <i>dubr-</i> ‘water, river’ is also possible for the first element. Places named <i>Rutherford</i> in West Linton (West Lothian) and Barningham (North Yorkshire) are less likely sources of the name."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Rotherforth was born in 1460, in York, Yorkshire, England, his father, Thomas Rotherforth II, was 30 and his mother, Lady Anna Haggerston, was 30. He married Constance Bradford in 1488, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1502, in his hometown, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1460–1502":"1460–1502","1470–1490":"1470–1490","1490–1523":"1490–1523","1430